<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1718,2034]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,297,1718,1745]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Distribution</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[315,400,1719,1745]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1086,1111]" captionTargetBox="[151,1398,174,1075]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[151,1398,174,1075]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 10. Records of Eoargiolestes ochraceus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3342263/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
). Genus endemic to Grande Terre. More than 30 localities are known from all over the island.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1718,2034]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,309,1790,1817]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Habitats.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Montrouzier" baseAuthorityYear="1864" box="[315,588,1791,1817]" class="Insecta" family="Argiolestidae" genus="Eoargiolestes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ochraceus">
<emphasis box="[315,588,1791,1817]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Eoargiolestes ochraceus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
prefers creeks with sunny reaches, on moderate slopes and with a rocky bed. It is rarer in the shaded upper parts of mountain creeks.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1718,2034]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,473,1862,1889]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Biology and behaviour.</emphasis>
Larvae were described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Lieftinck, M." box="[772,959,1863,1890]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" pagination="165 - 200" refId="ref33832" refString="Lieftinck, M. (1976) The dragonflies (Odonata) of New Caledonia and the Loyalty Islands - Part 2. Immature stages. Cahiers Office de la recherche scientifique et technique outre-mer (ORSTOM), Serie Hydrobiologie, 10, 165 - 200." type="journal article" year="1976">Lieftinck (1976)</bibRefCitation>
. Exuviae are found very close to the water, generally less than 
<quantity box="[365,433,1899,1926]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" unit="cm" value="20.0">20 cm</quantity>
from the water surface. Males are territorial and remain perched for long periods on rocks near the water surface. They drive off other males venturing into their territory.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1718,2034]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,281,1970,1997]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Status.</emphasis>
This species is widely distributed, with large populations. The main threat to its survival is the pollution of creeks and rivers. We consider this species to be LC.
</paragraph>
